did.abstract: The collection includes personal office files, teaching aids, sheet music, and Moffit arrangements of SWC school fight songs. It also contains complete shows for marching band, as well as general formation patterns. There are original Moffit working scores, formations/shows for the Michigan State University Marching Band, the University of Houston Marching Band, and the Purdue University “All-American” Marching Band. It also includes the Patterns of Motion material, ephemera, and awards. Materials range in date from the 1930s to 2008.

bioghist.head: Biographical Information:
bioghist.p: William C. Moffit was a band director of national importance, whose contributions to musical education gained many honors. He was born in Canton, Ohio on May 13, 1925 and joined the Coast Guard after high school, where he played in the Coast Guard Band. After the end of World War II, he attended Baldwin Wallace College on the GI Bill and attained his degree in 1950. He taught in the public school systems of Ohio and Michigan for ten years before joining the faculty at Michigan State University as a band director, where he taught for nine years. In 1969 he became the Director of the University of Houston Marching Band, where he taught until 1981. Bill Moffit resigned from the University of Houston to take a job at Purdue University, where he taught until his early retirement in 1988. After retiring, he founded the Jacksonville Community Concert Band in Jacksonville, Florida. He is the author of Soundpower, a collection of more than 450 arrangements for marching band and the Patterns of Motion concept in marching. Bill Moffit was the Director of the Fanfare Trumpets at the 1984 Olympics and the Director of the Fanfare Trumpets at the Pan American Games in 1986. The recipient of many honors and awards, he was nominated for the presentation of the Presidential Medal of Freedom and named “Music Arranger Laureate of Indiana” in 1988. His talents as a clinician, a guest conductor, and an adjudicator for music festivals were coveted by many institutions across the country. Bill Moffit died in 2008.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The William C. Moffit collection contains 44 cartons. The collection is organized into 14 series: Personal/Office Files, Teaching Materials, Sheet Music, University Fight Songs, Moffit Arrangements of SWC Fight Songs, Small Sectional Sheet Music, Moffit’s Resource Materials and Michigan State Band Books, Original Working Scores, Formations, Audio Cassettes and Records, Ephemera, Music Books, Awards, and Oversize material.

The collection includes personal office files, teaching aids, sheet music, and Moffit arrangements of SWC school fight songs. It also contains complete shows for marching band, as well as general formation patterns. There are original Moffit working scores, formations/shows for the Michigan State University Marching Band, the University of Houston Marching Band, and the Purdue University “All-American” Marching Band. It also includes the Patterns of Motion material, ephemera, and awards. Materials range in date from the 1930s to 2008.

For preservation and access reasons the collection has been re-boxed and re-foldered. New folder titles conform, as closely as possible, to original folder titles, except when the original was obviously incomplete, incorrect, or confusing. Original folder and item order has been maintained whenever possible. Exceptions were made when folders were obviously misfiled or when no order was apparent.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains 2 boxes of William C. Moffit’s personal and office files. Material includes correspondence, budget information, accounting, meeting agendas, royalties, copyright files, and memos. Also included is biographical material on Moffit, as well as his handwritten letters and notes. This series is arranged alphabetically. Oversized personal/office files can be found in OVS Box 61. Original folder and item order has been maintained whenever possible. Exceptions were made when folders were obviously misfiled or when no order was apparent.

scopecontent.p: This series contains 3 boxes of a variety of teaching aids and articles referenced by William C. Moffit. Materials related to “Finger Busters” may also be found in OVS Box 61. Original folder and item order has been maintained whenever possible. Exceptions were made when folders were obviously misfiled or when no order was apparent.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains 3 boxes of sheet music used by William C. Moffit as research for his marching band arrangements. Music includes various classic children’s songs, traditional university songs, and the 1984 “Olympic Fanfare.” Material is arranged alphabetically. The sheet music ranges in date from 1944 to 1986, with the bulk of the dated material coming from the 1960s. Oversized sheet music may be found in OVS Box 61 and 62. Research materials used during Moffit's time at teh Jacksonville Community Band may be found in Series 17, Jacksonville Community Band Materials. Original folder and item order has been maintained whenever possible. Exceptions were made when folders were obviously misfiled or when no order was apparent.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Patterns of Motion, by William C. Moffit, was a marching style featuring band members in constantly changing kaleidoscope patterns. This new marching band style, created by Moffit, quickly became a new trend and continues to impact contemporary marching band styles. This sub-series contains some basic formation designs that make up “Patterns of Motion.” It is arranged alphabetically and consists of 2 boxes. Oversized Patterns of Motion material may be found in OVS Box 59. Original folder and item order has been maintained whenever possible. Exceptions were made when folders were obviously misfiled or when no order was apparent.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series consists of materials used by William C. Moffit in his role as founder of the Jacksonville Community Band. Materials include scores, manuscript parts, and published arrangements used by the Jacksonville Community Band. Additional research material can be found in Series 3. Additional manuscript parts can be found in Series 6. Additional published arrangements by William Moffit can be found in Series 9. Additional published music books can be found in Series 15. This series contains 59 folders and original folder and item order has be maintained whenever possible. Oversize materials can be found in OVS Box 60.
